description.plain:
The Australian singer-songwriter, whose real name is James Keogh, described the inspiration for his stage name:

I got my name from a book called Bliss by Peter Carey, which is an Australian story. I had about five or six songs I was really stoked with, and I just wanted to have a name to put with that new collection of songs that wasn’t my name, because people always mispronounce Keough because it’s got the ‘gh’ at the end. So I used Vance Joy, which is a character [in the book] — he’s like a storyteller, so it’s a cool name.

description.plain:
The intro and first single to Vance Joy’s debut EP God Loves You When You’re Dancing was a critical and commercial success. Critics praised its clever lyrics filled with pop culture references. It peaked at 30 on the Billboard Hot 100 charts.

It is a weird mish-mash of ideas. Sometimes, you know, I will try to write and stick a bunch of different ideas and images together and it won’t work and I’ll think, “oh, that doesn’t sound right” or “it sounds too weird and it all conflicts with each other,” but for some reason that all came together well for “Riptide,” and when things happen like that it is a bit beyond your control. I had a bunch of different ideas and words, it wasn’t even a general story line like I was referring to an experience or anything. It is more like a stream of consciousness. – Vance Joy



According to an interview with American Songwriter, the song remained untouched and unfinished for four years from when Vance started writing it in 2008 until 2012. During long afternoons while his roommate was at work, he would work on it bit by bit. One day after a brief trip to the store, he returned home and played the melody on the ukulele, which he built on to finish the song a few days later.

description.plain:
“Georgia” is the sixth single off Vance Joy’s critically acclaimed album, Dream Your Life Away.  Released in February of 2015 and charting high on the Australian ARIA Chart, the song proved to show Joy’s debut album was gaining traction.

With its understated folk-style guitar picking working as the backbone, the vocal melodies carry this homage to love and all its complexities and seeming contradictions to great heights.  Joy gives a subtle nod to Ray Charles' 1960 hit, “Georgia On My Mind,” which later became the official song of the State.

description.plain:
“Fire and the Flood” appears on the deluxe edition of Australian singer-songwriter Vance Joy’s Dream Your Life Away.

Vance takes on the perspective of a stalker who can’t get over his failed relationship, haunted by the memories he shared with his ex.

He released the song and music video with a press release, saying:

I had a recurring image in my head of a guy walking in the neighbourhood where his ex-girlfriend lives. He is haunting the places they used to go together. He has time on his hands and feels kind of useless. He thinks that when they are back together he’ll be at peace again.

And so, “Fire and the Flood” joins the likes of stalker serenades such as: “Every Breath You Take”, “I Will Posess Your Heart”, “The Stalker”, and “Lily (My One and Only”.

description.plain:
“Lay It On Me” is the lead off single off Vance Joy’s second studio LP.  The song released July 12, 2017 and radio-premiered one day later on Triple J.

According to Vance Joy, “Lay It On Me” has been in the works for some time now:

I had this guitar riff I had been playing for ages but had never found a home for. When it was glued together with a lyric I had in my phone, ‘everything starts at your skin,’ the song started to make sense.

In support of this track, he announced a few tour dates in which he will share the stage with fellow Aussie artist Gretta Ray.

description.plain:
“From Afar” explores those relationships that you want but for whatever reason, will never have.

On September 17, 2016 at the CityFolk festival in Ottawa, Ontario, before playing, Vance Joy describes the song, explaining:

This next one is about wanting to have someone that you can’t because they’re just out of reach. Maybe they’re seeing someone else, or maybe you’re seeing someone.  When I was faced with that, I decided to write a song to let it all out and to be free of it.

In the music video, a young boy is duped by the boy he loves and deserted as his lover escapes with a girl. The video illustrates the notion of unattainable love.

At the end of the song, the protagonist realises his love for her was just based on physical attractiveness.

“First Time” was released in August of 2014 as Vance Joy’s fourth single off his debut album, Dream Your Life Away.  The song charted in both his country of Australia as well as Belgium.

As a part of Vance Joy’s debut album, Dream Your Life Away, this song was released on September 5th, 2014.
